---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';

const appSchema = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "SoftwareApplication",
  "name": "Dimensional Weight Calculator for Shopify Sellers",
  "description": "Calculate DIM weight, billable weight, and potential savings across USPS, UPS, FedEx, and DHL for Shopify shipments",
  "applicationCategory": "BusinessApplication",
  "operatingSystem": "Any",
  "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0", "priceCurrency": "USD" }
});

const faqSchema = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is dimensional weight (DIM weight)?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Dimensional weight, also called DIM weight or volumetric weight, is a pricing technique used by carriers to account for the space a package occupies relative to its actual weight. It is calculated by multiplying the package length, width, and height (in inches) and dividing by a carrier-specific DIM divisor. Carriers charge based on whichever is greater: the actual weight or the DIM weight."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What DIM divisors do USPS, UPS, FedEx, and DHL use?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "As of 2024, the DIM divisors are: USPS uses 166, while UPS, FedEx, and DHL all use 139. A lower divisor means DIM weight is calculated higher, so carriers with a divisor of 139 will charge DIM weight more often than USPS for the same package dimensions."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How can I reduce DIM weight charges on my Shopify orders?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The most effective way to reduce DIM weight charges is to use the smallest box that safely fits your product. Switch from rigid boxes to poly mailers or padded envelopes for soft goods like clothing. Consider right-sizing your packaging inventory so you have multiple box sizes. You can also compare carriers — USPS uses a higher DIM divisor (166) compared to UPS and FedEx (139), which means USPS calculates a lower DIM weight for the same package."
      }
    }
  ]
});
---
<Base
  title="Dimensional Weight Calculator — DIM Weight for Shopify Shipping (Free)"
  description="Calculate dimensional (DIM) weight across USPS, UPS, FedEx, and DHL. See your billable weight and find out if you're overpaying on Shopify shipments."
  noWebAppSchema={true}
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={appSchema} />
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={faqSchema} />

  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Dimensional Weight Calculator</h1>
  <p class="text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 mb-8">
    Enter your box dimensions and actual weight to find the DIM weight and billable weight for each carrier. Works for USPS, UPS, FedEx, and DHL.
  </p>

  <div class="flex flex-col lg:flex-row gap-8 items-start">

    <!-- Input block -->
    <div class="w-full lg:w-1/2 space-y-6">

      <!-- Dimensions & weight -->
      <div class="border dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-5 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Package Dimensions &amp; Weight</p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 gap-4">
          <div>
            <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-1 dark:text-gray-300" for="dim-length">Length (in)</label>
            <input
              id="dim-length"
              type="number"
              min="0"
              step="0.1"
              placeholder="12"
              lang="en"
              inputmode="decimal"
              class="w-full border dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-teal-500"
            />
          </div>
          <div>
            <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-1 dark:text-gray-300" for="dim-width">Width (in)</label>
            <input
              id="dim-width"
              type="number"
              min="0"
              step="0.1"
              placeholder="10"
              lang="en"
              inputmode="decimal"
              class="w-full border dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-teal-500"
            />
          </div>
          <div>
            <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-1 dark:text-gray-300" for="dim-height">Height (in)</label>
            <input
              id="dim-height"
              type="number"
              min="0"
              step="0.1"
              placeholder="8"
              lang="en"
              inputmode="decimal"
              class="w-full border dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-teal-500"
            />
          </div>
          <div>
            <label class="block text-sm font-medium mb-1 dark:text-gray-300" for="actual-weight">Actual Weight (lbs)</label>
            <input
              id="actual-weight"
              type="number"
              min="0"
              step="0.1"
              placeholder="2"
              lang="en"
              inputmode="decimal"
              class="w-full border dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 dark:text-gray-100 focus:outline-none focus:ring-2 focus:ring-teal-500"
            />
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Carrier selector -->
      <div class="border dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-5 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300 mb-4">Select Carrier</p>
        <div class="grid grid-cols-2 sm:grid-cols-4 gap-3" id="carrier-buttons">
          <button
            type="button"
            data-carrier="USPS"
            data-divisor="166"
            class="carrier-btn border-2 border-teal-600 dark:border-teal-400 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-teal-700 dark:text-teal-400 bg-teal-50 dark:bg-teal-900/30 transition"
          >
            USPS
          </button>
          <button
            type="button"
            data-carrier="UPS"
            data-divisor="139"
            class="carrier-btn border-2 border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 hover:border-teal-500 transition"
          >
            UPS
          </button>
          <button
            type="button"
            data-carrier="FedEx"
            data-divisor="139"
            class="carrier-btn border-2 border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 hover:border-teal-500 transition"
          >
            FedEx
          </button>
          <button
            type="button"
            data-carrier="DHL"
            data-divisor="139"
            class="carrier-btn border-2 border-gray-200 dark:border-gray-600 rounded-lg px-3 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 bg-white dark:bg-gray-800 hover:border-teal-500 transition"
          >
            DHL
          </button>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-3">
          DIM divisor: <span id="divisor-display" class="font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">166</span>
          &nbsp;(USPS = 166; UPS, FedEx, DHL = 139)
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Tip box -->
      <div class="border dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-5 bg-teal-50 dark:bg-teal-900/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-teal-800 dark:text-teal-300 mb-1">Rule of thumb</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-teal-700 dark:text-teal-400">
          If a package is light for its size, DIM weight kicks in. A 12&times;10&times;8&Prime; box has a DIM weight of
          <strong>~5.8 lbs</strong> on UPS/FedEx (divisor 139), even if the contents weigh only 1 lb — and that's what
          you'll be billed for.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <!-- Results panel -->
    <div class="w-full lg:w-1/2 lg:sticky lg:top-6">
      <div class="border dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-5 bg-white dark:bg-gray-900 space-y-4">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">Results</p>

        <!-- DIM weight -->
        <div class="border dark:border-gray-700 rounded-xl p-4 bg-gray-50 dark:bg-gray-800">
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mb-1">DIM Weight</div>
          <div id="result-dim" class="text-3xl font-bold text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400">—</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 mt-1">lbs</div>
        </div>

        <!-- Billable weight (highlighted) -->
        <div class="border-2 border-teal-600 dark:border-teal-400 rounded-xl p-4 bg-teal-50 dark:bg-teal-900/30">
          <div class="text-xs text-teal-700 dark:text-teal-300 mb-1 font-semibold">Billable Weight — what you pay</div>
          <div id="result-billable" class="text-3xl font-bold text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400">—</div>
          <div class="text-xs text-teal-600 dark:text-teal-400 mt-1">lbs</div>
        </div>

        <!-- Status message -->
        <div id="result-status" class="rounded-xl p-4 border dark:border-gray-700 text-sm hidden"></div>

        <!-- Savings opportunity -->
        <div id="result-savings" class="rounded-xl p-4 border border-amber-300 dark:border-amber-700 bg-amber-50 dark:bg-amber-900/20 text-sm text-amber-800 dark:text-amber-300 hidden"></div>

        <!-- Actual weight reference -->
        <div class="flex justify-between items-center text-sm text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400 px-1">
          <span>Actual weight</span>
          <span id="result-actual" class="font-medium text-gray-700 dark:text-gray-300">—</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script>
    // --- State ---
    let activeDivisor: number = 166;
    let activeCarrier: string = 'USPS';

    // --- DOM refs ---
    const lengthEl   = document.getElementById('dim-length')    as HTMLInputElement;
    const widthEl    = document.getElementById('dim-width')     as HTMLInputElement;
    const heightEl   = document.getElementById('dim-height')    as HTMLInputElement;
    const weightEl   = document.getElementById('actual-weight') as HTMLInputElement;
    const divisorEl  = document.getElementById('divisor-display') as HTMLElement;

    const resultDim      = document.getElementById('result-dim')      as HTMLElement;
    const resultBillable = document.getElementById('result-billable') as HTMLElement;
    const resultStatus   = document.getElementById('result-status')   as HTMLElement;
    const resultSavings  = document.getElementById('result-savings')  as HTMLElement;
    const resultActual   = document.getElementById('result-actual')   as HTMLElement;

    // --- Carrier buttons ---
    const carrierBtns = document.querySelectorAll<HTMLButtonElement>('.carrier-btn');

    function setActiveCarrier(btn: HTMLButtonElement): void {
      carrierBtns.forEach(b => {
        b.classList.remove(
          'border-teal-600', 'dark:border-teal-400',
          'text-teal-700', 'dark:text-teal-400',
          'bg-teal-50', 'dark:bg-teal-900/30'
        );
        b.classList.add(
          'border-gray-200', 'dark:border-gray-600',
          'text-gray-600', 'dark:text-gray-300',
          'bg-white', 'dark:bg-gray-800'
        );
      });
      btn.classList.remove(
        'border-gray-200', 'dark:border-gray-600',
        'text-gray-600', 'dark:text-gray-300',
        'bg-white', 'dark:bg-gray-800'
      );
      btn.classList.add(
        'border-teal-600', 'dark:border-teal-400',
        'text-teal-700', 'dark:text-teal-400',
        'bg-teal-50', 'dark:bg-teal-900/30'
      );
      activeDivisor = parseInt(btn.dataset.divisor ?? '166', 10);
      activeCarrier = btn.dataset.carrier ?? 'USPS';
      divisorEl.textContent = String(activeDivisor);
      calculate();
    }

    carrierBtns.forEach(btn => {
      btn.addEventListener('click', () => setActiveCarrier(btn));
    });

    // --- Calculation ---
    function calculate(): void {
      const L = parseFloat(lengthEl.value) || 0;
      const W = parseFloat(widthEl.value)  || 0;
      const H = parseFloat(heightEl.value) || 0;
      const actual = parseFloat(weightEl.value) || 0;

      const hasInput = L > 0 && W > 0 && H > 0;

      if (!hasInput) {
        resultDim.textContent      = '—';
        resultBillable.textContent = '—';
        resultActual.textContent   = actual > 0 ? actual.toLocaleString('en-US', { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 }) + ' lbs' : '—';
        resultStatus.classList.add('hidden');
        resultSavings.classList.add('hidden');
        return;
      }

      const dimWeight      = (L * W * H) / activeDivisor;
      const billableWeight = Math.max(actual, dimWeight);
      const isDimBilling   = dimWeight > actual;

      // Format numbers
      const fmtLbs = (n: number) =>
        n.toLocaleString('en-US', { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });

      resultDim.textContent      = fmtLbs(dimWeight);
      resultBillable.textContent = fmtLbs(billableWeight);
      resultActual.textContent   = actual > 0 ? fmtLbs(actual) + ' lbs' : '—';

      // Status
      resultStatus.classList.remove('hidden');
      if (isDimBilling) {
        resultStatus.className =
          'rounded-xl p-4 border border-red-200 dark:border-red-800 bg-red-50 dark:bg-red-900/20 text-sm text-red-700 dark:text-red-400';
        resultStatus.textContent =
          `You're being billed by DIM weight on ${activeCarrier}. Your box is larger than its contents justify.`;

        const excess = dimWeight - actual;
        resultSavings.classList.remove('hidden');
        resultSavings.innerHTML =
          `<strong>Savings opportunity:</strong> You're paying for an extra ${fmtLbs(excess)} lbs per package. ` +
          `Reducing your box size could eliminate this DIM surcharge. Consider a smaller box or poly mailers for soft goods.`;
      } else {
        resultStatus.className =
          'rounded-xl p-4 border border-green-200 dark:border-green-800 bg-green-50 dark:bg-green-900/20 text-sm text-green-700 dark:text-green-400';
        resultStatus.textContent =
          `You're billed by actual weight on ${activeCarrier} — your package is dense enough that DIM weight doesn't apply.`;
        resultSavings.classList.add('hidden');
      }
    }

    // --- Live calculation on input ---
    [lengthEl, widthEl, heightEl, weightEl].forEach(el => {
      el.addEventListener('input', calculate);
    });
  </script>

  <!-- SEO Content -->
  <section class="mt-16 prose dark:prose-invert max-w-3xl">
    <h2>What Is Dimensional Weight and Why It Matters for Shopify Shipping</h2>
    <p>
      Dimensional weight — often shortened to DIM weight or volumetric weight — is a billing method used by every major
      carrier to account for the physical space a package occupies in their network, not just how heavy it is. A carrier's
      trucks, planes, and sorting facilities have limited cubic volume. A large, lightweight box takes up as much space as
      a dense, heavy one, so carriers developed DIM weight pricing to make light-but-bulky shippers pay their fair share
      of capacity costs.
    </p>
    <p>
      The formula is straightforward: multiply the length, width, and height of your package in inches, then divide by
      the carrier's DIM divisor. USPS uses a divisor of 166, while UPS, FedEx, and DHL all use 139. A lower divisor
      produces a higher DIM weight, which means UPS, FedEx, and DHL will trigger DIM billing more often than USPS for
      the same package.
    </p>
    <p>
      Once the DIM weight is calculated, the carrier compares it to the actual (scale) weight of your shipment and bills
      you for whichever is greater. If your actual weight is 2 lbs but the DIM weight is 5.8 lbs, you pay for 5.8 lbs —
      even though you only dropped 2 lbs on the scale. For Shopify sellers shipping lightweight items like clothing,
      supplements, or electronics accessories in generously sized boxes, this can silently add dollars to every single
      order.
    </p>

    <h3>When Does DIM Weight Apply?</h3>
    <p>
      USPS applies DIM weight only to packages over 1 cubic foot (1,728 cubic inches) for Priority Mail and Priority Mail
      Express. For everything under that threshold, USPS charges actual weight only — a meaningful advantage for smaller
      packages. UPS and FedEx apply DIM weight to all packages regardless of size when shipped via ground or air
      services. DHL applies it to all international express shipments. This is why carrier selection matters: a 10×8×6
      box (480 cubic inches) avoids DIM billing on USPS but triggers it on UPS.
    </p>
    <p>
      Shopify sellers are particularly vulnerable to DIM weight surprises during peak season when they switch to
      pre-assembled box kits, or when they start selling new products with different size-to-weight ratios. Running every
      new SKU through a DIM weight calculator before launching is a simple habit that protects your margins.
    </p>

    <h2>How to Reduce Your DIM Weight Charges</h2>

    <h3>Use the Smallest Box That Safely Fits Your Product</h3>
    <p>
      The single highest-impact change you can make is right-sizing your packaging. Stock several box sizes rather than
      relying on one universal box. A product that fits in a 9×6×4 box instead of a 12×10×6 box reduces the cubic
      volume by more than 70%, potentially taking the shipment below the DIM weight threshold entirely. Folded cardboard
      inserts and paper fill let you ship in a smaller box without sacrificing protection.
    </p>

    <h3>Switch to Poly Mailers for Soft Goods</h3>
    <p>
      Clothing, fabric accessories, and other compressible items are ideal candidates for poly mailers or padded bubble
      envelopes. A poly mailer containing a folded t-shirt might measure 14×11×1 — an extremely low DIM weight even at
      a divisor of 139. The same shirt in a rigid box for presentation purposes could add $1–3 to your shipping cost on
      every order. Reserve rigid boxes for products that genuinely require them.
    </p>

    <h3>Compare Carriers Based on Your Actual Box Dimensions</h3>
    <p>
      Because USPS uses a higher DIM divisor (166 vs. 139), it calculates a lower DIM weight for the same package. For
      packages under 1 cubic foot, USPS charges actual weight only. This makes USPS especially competitive for
      lightweight items in smaller boxes shipping domestically. Use this calculator to compare what each carrier would
      bill for your specific package before you commit to a carrier contract or Shopify shipping integration.
    </p>

    <h3>Zone-Based Carrier Selection</h3>
    <p>
      Shipping costs scale with both weight and distance (zones). If your DIM weight is unavoidable — say, you sell a
      lightweight lamp that requires a large box — focus on minimizing the zone distance instead. Distributing inventory
      across multiple fulfillment centers can reduce zones and offset the DIM penalty. Shopify's multi-location inventory
      makes this easier to manage than it once was.
    </p>

    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <h3 id="faq-what-is-dim-weight">What is dimensional weight (DIM weight)?</h3>
    <p>
      Dimensional weight is a carrier pricing method that assigns a theoretical weight to a package based on its volume.
      The formula is: DIM weight = (L &times; W &times; H in inches) &divide; DIM divisor. Carriers charge the greater
      of the actual scale weight or the calculated DIM weight. This prevents shippers from sending large, nearly-empty
      boxes at bargain prices.
    </p>

    <h3 id="faq-divisors">What DIM divisors do USPS, UPS, FedEx, and DHL use?</h3>
    <p>
      USPS uses a DIM divisor of 166. UPS, FedEx, and DHL each use a divisor of 139. A lower divisor produces a
      higher DIM weight for the same package dimensions — meaning UPS, FedEx, and DHL will apply DIM billing more
      aggressively than USPS. Note that USPS only applies DIM weight to packages larger than 1 cubic foot, while the
      other carriers apply it to all package sizes.
    </p>

    <h3 id="faq-reduce-charges">How can I reduce DIM weight charges on my Shopify orders?</h3>
    <p>
      The most effective strategies are: (1) use the smallest box that safely contains your product, (2) switch to poly
      mailers or padded envelopes for compressible items like clothing or fabric goods, (3) compare carriers using a DIM
      weight calculator before selecting a shipping partner, and (4) consider USPS for small packages under 1 cubic foot
      since USPS does not apply DIM weight below that threshold. Every dollar saved on shipping per order compounds
      significantly at scale.
    </p>
  </section>
</Base>
